eri</i> ‘army’. This surname is rare in East Frisia.","English (London): habitational name from Gastard (Wiltshire), named with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ (genitive plural <i>gāta</i>) + <i>steort</i> ‘tail of land’, meaning ‘goats' tail of land’.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gastard</i>, a compound of <i>gast</i> ‘guest, foreigner’, earlier ‘foreign warrior’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, strong’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jaster","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Gunther, Heinz, Helmut, Herta, Otto, Reinhard, Siegfried.","North German, East Frisian, and North Frisian: variant of   Gaster  . This surname is very rare in North Frisia."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":5,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705187,"age":114,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Meurdracs de Gaste was born in 1101, in Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, England, his father, Denis Everard de Gaste, was 26 and his mother, Meurdracs, was 17. He married de Geroie about 1125, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Wiltshire, England, and was buried in Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1101–":"1101–Surnud","1101–Male":"1101–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1126–1186":"1126–1186","1075–Male":"1075–Surnud","1084–Female":"1084–Surnud","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1126":"1126","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","about 1125":"umbes 1125","1186":"1186","1075":"1075","1084":"1084","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","St Peter Churchyard, Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire Unitary Authority, Wiltshire, England":"Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, England":"Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1101–":"1101–Kuollut","1101–Male":"1101–Kuollut","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","1126–1186":"1126–1186","1075–Male":"1075–Kuollut","1084–Female":"1084–Kuollut","1106":"1106","1215":"1215","1126":"1126","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","about 1125":"noin 1125","1186":"1186","1075":"1075","1084":"1084","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","St Peter Churchyard, Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire Unitary Authority, Wiltshire, England":"Swallowcliffe, Wiltshire, Engla